snippet.textDisplay: Am I wrong or are you pushing the very edge of performance to both get that payload of 60 sats into desired orbit AND recover the booster at sea?  If this is the case, I would not call the landing attempt a "failure".  More like squeezing every ounce of performance out of the launch system...and this time there wasn't enough left for a safe recovery on the ship.  Question:  Did the 1st stage get so low on fuel that it intentionally soft-landed in the water to avoid the risk of damaging itself and the drone ship?  Or, did it indeed have a malfunction...an unexpected condition?  If this was simply a safety maneuver...a risk minimizing action at fuel or oxidizer exhaustion...I think it's important to make that clear.  Because otherwise, media will just chalk it up as another failure.  When it comes to flying people on Starship, Congress will remember all these Falcon 9 landing "failures" when Starship will probably never push the edge like this.

snippet.textDisplay:
Man! The FAA should only have a say in space launches AFTER they launch something into space while catching the rocket used for the launch.
The only thing they should be needed for is for SpaceX to call and say "We are launching, clear the airspace."
If the FAA were to say no to the launch, I feel it would merely be the beginning of the no parade.
I am ALL for safe AIR travel. But if the vehicle will be beyond aircraft height in mere moments, their say should be as minimal as possible. As in only clearing the airspace around the launch site and trajectory.

Simply put, Elon has no ill intentions. He will not lead us astray. If he wants to launch, that's exactly what he should be able to do, FAA be damned.

And no, I am unsure as to why this is getting under my skin. I am just sick of people not "in the know" having any say regarding those who DO know. And I feel the genius minds employed by SpaceX should not have to ask permission as much as they currently do. If he starts burning tires, or starts dumping oil into the ocean, THEN interrupt.
But when progressing our species while making milestone achievements which do no harm to life, step back and let it happen.

snippet.textDisplay:
YES! I can't wait to get my Starlink internet setup! (Willing to participate in Alpha testing ;) ).

Let's just stop and appreciate how, after coming down from a suborbital flight, an unmanned 1st stage was something like 30 feet (?) off a floating barge, in the middle of the ocean, after coming down 331'365 feet. PLUS, it was still a soft landing from what I heard, didn't even crash.

30 out of 331'365? Not too bad if you ask me! Successful deployment of the satellites (the most important part). Barge landings, not 1st stage recovery, I mean actually landing in that tiny thing, is but the cherry on top.

KEEP IT UP SPACE X!
